Blockchain Technology Used by Andhra Pradesh Government (Land Records)


The Government of Andhra Pradesh (GoAP) has adopted blockchain technology to modernize land and real-estate record management. 
This initiative focuses on improving transparency, preventing fraud, and ensuring secure ownership records through digital governance.

Who Introduced It?
Introduced by the Revenue Department, Government of Andhra Pradesh
Implemented through digital platforms like MeeBhoomi (launched in 2015) and Webland / Webland 2.0
Supported by successive AP governments under the Digital India initiative

How Blockchain Is Used
  Blockchain secures land ownership history and mutation records
  Each property transaction is recorded against a Unique Land Parcel Number
  Backend blockchain modules ensure records are tamper-proof and traceable
  Citizens access records through the MeeBhoomi portal

Benefits of Blockchain in AP Land Records
Ensures transparency and trust in land ownership data
Prevents tampering and fraudulent changes
Enables faster verification for citizens, banks, and government departments
Reduces corruption and manual intervention

Challenges / Defects
Errors in old records remain if incorrect data is entered
Digital literacy and internet access issues in rural areas
Requires large-scale resurvey and verification
Technical and infrastructure limitations

Summary (3 Points)
Andhra Pradesh uses blockchain to create secure and tamper-proof land records.
Digital platforms like MeeBhoomi and Webland improve transparency and access.
While effective, challenges remain in data accuracy and digital infrastructure.



